p, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Burgoyne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Burgundy (Middle English <i>Burgoin</i>, Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>, Latin <i>Burgundia</i>), a region of eastern France having Dijon as its center. The area was invaded by the <i>Burgundii</i>, an ancient Germanic tribe from whom it takes its name, in about  AD  480. The duchy of Burgundy, created in 877 by Charles II, King of the West Franks, was extremely powerful in the later Middle Ages, especially under Philip the Bold (1342–1404, duke from 1363)."],"variants":[{"name":"Burgin","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Burgundy, Old French <i>Bourgogne</i>, <i>Bourgoin</i> ‘the Burgundian’. Alternatively, from the synonymous name   Burgoyne  .","Swiss German (<b>Bürgin</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Burkhard</i> (see   Burkhart  )."]},{"name":"Burgamy","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of <b>Burgany</b>, itself a variant of   Burgoyne   (Middle English <i>Bourgoine</i>, <i>Burgonye</i> ‘Burgundy’). This form of the name is now rare or absent in Britain."]},{"name":"Burgoon","meanings":["English: variant of   Burgoyne  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <